  <text>
    <front>

      <titlePage>
        <docTitle>
          <titlePart>CMC-core</titlePart>
          <titlePart>TEI Customisation for CMC corpora</titlePart>
        </docTitle>
        <docEdition>Development version <date>2021-03-05T15Z</date></docEdition>
      </titlePage>
      
      <p>This ODD describes an encoding schema for genres of
      computer-mediated communication (CMC) including social media. It
      is meant to define a basic setup that one needs to encode CMC
      corpora, as a proposal for inclusion in the <title>TEI
      Guidelines</title>.</p>

      <divGen type="toc"/>

      <div type="section">
        <head>RATIONALE</head>
        <p> … … … </p>
      </div>

      <div type="section">
        <head>CUSTOMIZATION</head>

        <p>The schema defined herein introduces four types of customizations:
        <list>
          <item>A new module named <name type="module">cmc</name> is
          introduced. This module exists to hold the various new
          classes and the new <gi>post</gi> element. </item>
          <item>The new element <gi>post</gi> is introduced. </item>
          <item>The class <name type="class">model.CMC</name> is
          defined; the new <gi>post</gi> element is a member of it,
          and it, in turn, is a member of <name
          type="class">model.common</name>. (It is not clear to us
          whether the name should be <mentioned>model.CMC</mentioned>
          or <mentioned>model.cmc</mentioned>; the latter is much
          prettier, the former seems to follow TEI naming practices
          more precisely).</item>
          <item>The new attribute class <name
          type="class">att.CMC</name> is introduced. It defines the
          new attribute <att>generatedBy</att>. The <gi>post</gi>
          element and all its children are members of <name
          type="class">att.CMC</name>. (It is not clear to us
          whether the name should be <mentioned>att.CMC</mentioned>
          or <mentioned>att.cmc</mentioned>; the latter is much
          prettier, the former seems to follow TEI naming practices
          more precisely).</item>
        </list>
        </p>

        <p>In addition to this proposal, sample annotations using this
        schema are provided. (They can be found in the accompanying
        <name type="file">../data/</name> directory.) These samples
        cover various genres including private chat, IRC, twitter,
        Second Life, and Wikipedia talk.</p>
      </div>

      <div type="section">
        <head>STATUS OF THIS SCHEMA</head>
        <p>The schema originally accompanied a feature request by the
        TEI CMC SIG to the TEI in 2019, and came with encoded examples
        and documentation. It is now used as a direct working proposal
        to Council for inclusion in the <title>TEI Guidelines</title>,
        P5.</p>
      </div>

      <div type="section">
        <head>REFERENCES</head>

        <p><bibl>Michael Beißwenger, Laura Herzberg, Harald Lüngen,
        Ciara R. Wigham: CMC-core: A basic schema for encoding CMC
        corpora in TEI. Conference poster, 7th Conference on CMC and
        Social Media Corpora for the Humanities (CMC-Corpora2019).
        University Cergy-Pontoise, Paris, France, September 9, 2019.</bibl>
        (<ref
        target="https://www.uni-due.de/germanistik/chatkorpus/tei/cmccore/poster_teicmccore_2019-08-31.pdf"
        >conference poster as pdf</ref> | <ref
        target="https://cmccorpora19.sciencesconf.org/resource/page/id/15">abstract
        in conference proceedings</ref>)</p>

        <p><bibl>Michael Beißwenger, Harald Lüngen (2019, submitted):
        CMC-core: a schema for the representation of CMC corpora in
        TEI.</bibl> Journal article, preview version on request.</p>

        <p>Description of the Chat2CLARIN schema: <bibl
        xml:id="chat2clarin"> Harald Lüngen, Michael Beißwenger, Erik
        Ehrhardt, Axel Herold, Angelika Storrer (2016): <ref
        target="https://www.linguistics.rub.de/konvens16/pub/20_konvensproc.pdf"
        >Integrating corpora of computer-mediated communication in
        CLARIN-D: Results from the curation project
        ChatCorpus2CLARIN.</ref> In: Proceedings of the 13th
        Conference on Natural Language Processing (KONVENS 2016).
        Ruhr-Universität Bochum. </bibl></p>

        <p xml:id="descmr">Description of the CoMeRe project:
        <bibl>Chanier, T., Poudat, C., Sagot, B., Antoniadis, G.,
        Wigham, C. R. , Hriba, L.,Longhi, J. &amp; Seddah, D. (2014) «
        The CoMeRe corpus for French: structuring and annotating
        heterogeneous CMC genres ». Special issue on « Building And
        Annotating Corpora Of Computer-Mediated Discourse: Issues and
        Challenges at the Interface of Corpus and Computational
        Linguistics ». <ref
        target="http://www.jlcl.org/2014_Heft2/Heft2-2014.pdf ">JLCL
        (Journal of Language Technology and Computational
        Linguistics), pp. 1-31</ref></bibl></p>
        
        <p>Description of the DeRiK schema: <bibl
        xml:id="TEIcmc2012">Michael Beißwenger, Maria Ermakova,
        Alexander Geyken, Lothar Lemnitzer, and Angelika Storrer
        (2012). « A TEI Schema for the Representation of
        Computer-mediated Communication », Journal of the Text
        Encoding Initiative, Issue 3. <ref
        target="http://jtei.revues.org/476"><idno>DOI :
        10.4000/jtei.476</idno></ref></bibl></p>
      </div>
